06528nam a22008775i 9780674275928DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19971997mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742759287 a10.4159/97806742759282doi  a(DE-B1597)626022  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJK1764b.W49 1997 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a306.2/0973/0904922100aWhy People Don’t Trust Government /ced. by Philip D. Zelikow, David C. King, Joseph S. Nye Jr. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Decline of Confidence in Government -- tPART ONE The Scope and Performance of Government -- tOne. The Evolving Scope of Government -- tTwo. Measuring the Performance of Government -- tThree. Fall from Grace: The Public’s Loss of Faith in Government -- tPART TWO. The Menu of Explanations -- tFour. Is It Really the Economy, Stupid? -- tFive. Social and Cultural Causes of Dissatisfaction with U.S. Government -- tSix. The Polarization of American Parties and Mistrust of Government -- tSeven. The Politics of Mistrust -- tPART THREE. Data on Public Attitudes Toward Governance -- tEight. Changing Attitudes in America -- tNine. Postmateralist Values and the Erosion of Institutional Authority -- tTen. Public Trust and Democracy in Japan -- tConclusion: Reflections, Conjectures, and Puzzles -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConfidence in American government has been declining for three decades. Three-quarters of Americans said they trusted the Federal government to do the right thing in 1964. Today, only a quarter do. Why the decline? Is this mistrust a healthy reflection of America's long-lasting skepticism of a strong state? Is mistrust a problem for the future of governance? Bringing together essays by leading Harvard scholars, this book explores the roots of mistrust. It first examines government's current scope, its actual performance, and citizens' perceptions of its performance. It then assesses many possible explanations that have been offered for the decline of trust, including the end of the Cold War, elevated expectations following World War II, a weakened economy, the effects of globalization, resentment over political scandals, and incompetence of bureaucrats. The book clarifies thinking about the sources of public disaffection. Mistrust, the contributors find, is largely unrelated to national economic conditions, to challenges of a global economy, to the Cold War, or to bumbling bureaucrats and venal politicians. Rather, they show that the most likely culprits are all around us—an interacting blend of cultural and political conflicts stirred by an increasingly corrosive news media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAllegiancezUnited States. 0aPolitical alienationzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAltman, Drew E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenson, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlendon, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBok, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodie, Mollyann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrossard, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInglehart, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Matt, econtributor.4ctb